**Sec. 70001**
This section establishes that all references to the Internal Revenue Code of 1986 in this title apply to that Code unless expressly stated otherwise. It further specifies that the special rate change rules under Section 15 of the Internal Revenue Code do not apply to any tax rate changes enacted by this title. These provisions serve as the foundational definitions for interpreting the subsequent tax amendments.

**Sec. 70101**
This section permanently extends the individual income tax rate brackets established by the 2017 Tax Cuts and Jobs Act, removing the scheduled expiration date of December 31, 2025. It also modifies the inflation adjustment mechanism for the 12 percent and 22 percent brackets to begin at the 2017 base year rather than 2016. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70102**
This section permanently extends the increased standard deduction amounts and permanently raises the specific dollar thresholds for single and joint filers. It increases the standard deduction for single filers to $23,625 and for joint filers to $47,250 (calculated as $23,625 per spouse), replacing the previous $18,000 and $36,000 figures. Additionally, it adjusts the inflation indexing base year to 2024 for future calculations. These amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70103**
This section terminates the general deduction for personal exemptions but creates a temporary $6,000 deduction for taxpayers and spouses aged 65 or older. This senior deduction is available for taxable years beginning before January 1, 2029, and phases out for taxpayers with modified adjusted gross income exceeding $75,000 ($150,000 for joint returns) at a rate of 6 percent. The deduction requires the inclusion of a valid Social Security number for each qualified individual. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70104**
This section permanently extends the expanded Child Tax Credit, increasing the credit amount from $2,000 to $2,200 per qualifying child. It mandates that a valid Social Security number issued by the Social Security Administration must be present for both the taxpayer and the child to claim the credit. The refundable portion of the credit is set at $1,400 and will be subject to inflation adjustments starting in 2025. These amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70105**
This section permanently extends the Qualified Business Income (QBI) deduction and increases the taxable income phase-in thresholds to $75,000 for single filers and $150,000 for joint filers. It establishes a minimum deduction of $400 for taxpayers with at least $1,000 of active qualified business income. The $400 minimum and the $1,000 income threshold will be subject to inflation adjustments beginning in 2026. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70106**
This section permanently increases the estate and gift tax exemption amount from $5,000,000 to $15,000,000 per person. It adjusts the inflation indexing base year for the exemption amount to calendar year 2025. These provisions apply to estates of decedents dying and gifts made after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70107**
This section permanently extends the increased Alternative Minimum Tax (AMT) exemption amounts and modifies the phaseout thresholds. It increases the AMT exemption for single filers to $109,400 and for joint filers to $1,000,000, with the phaseout rate increasing from 25 percent to 50 percent for high-income taxpayers. The inflation adjustment base year for the $1,000,000 exemption is set to 2025. These amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70108**
This section permanently extends the limitation on the deduction for qualified residence interest and clarifies that mortgage insurance premiums are treated as interest. It removes the expiration date of December 31, 2025, for the existing rules regarding home mortgage interest deductions. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70109**
This section permanently extends the limitation on casualty loss deductions and expands the definition of a "disaster" to include those declared by a State Governor. Taxpayers may now deduct losses from State-declared disasters, which include natural catastrophes and fires, provided the damage severity warrants such application. The term "State" includes the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, the Virgin Islands, Guam, American Samoa, and the Northern Mariana Islands. These amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70110**
This section permanently extends the suspension of miscellaneous itemized deductions but creates a permanent exception for educator expenses. It expands the definition of educator expenses to include coaches and nonathletic instructional equipment for health or physical education courses. The deduction for these expenses is no longer subject to the 2 percent of adjusted gross income floor. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70111**
This section reinstates the Pease limitation on itemized deductions, reducing the total amount of itemized deductions by two-thirds of the amount by which taxable income exceeds the 37 percent tax bracket threshold. This limitation applies after other specific deduction limitations but does not affect the calculation of the Qualified Business Income deduction. The provision applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70112**
This section permanently extends the rules for qualified transportation fringe benefits and removes the exclusion for bicycle commuting reimbursements. It also eliminates the exclusion for qualified parking and transit passes that were previously subject to specific limitations. The inflation adjustment base year for these benefits is set to 1997. These amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70113**
This section permanently extends the limitation on the deduction and exclusion for moving expenses, while simultaneously creating a new exception for members of the intelligence community. Employees or new appointees of the intelligence community who relocate due to a change in assignment are now treated the same as Armed Forces members for moving expense purposes. This exception applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70114**
This section modifies the deduction for wagering losses by limiting the allowable deduction to 90 percent of the total losses incurred during the taxable year. The deduction remains limited to the extent of wagering gains for the year. This change applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70115**
This section permanently extends the increased annual contribution limit for ABLE accounts, which is tied to the gift tax exclusion amount. It adjusts the inflation indexing base year for the ABLE account contribution limit to 1996. These amendments apply to contributions made after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70116**
This section permanently extends the Saver's Credit to include contributions made to ABLE accounts and increases the maximum credit amount from $2,000 to $2,100. It also repeals a prior amendment from the SECURE 2.0 Act that had limited the credit's application to certain retirement savings. The credit increase applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2026.

**Sec. 70117**
This section permanently extends the rule permitting rollovers from qualified tuition programs (529 plans) to ABLE accounts. It removes the expiration date of December 31, 2026, for these tax-free rollovers. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70118**
This section makes permanent the tax exclusion for special pay received by members of the Armed Forces serving in the Sinai Peninsula. It expands the list of qualified hazardous duty areas to include Kenya, Mali, Burkina Faso, and Chad. These provisions take effect on January 1, 2026.

**Sec. 70119**
This section permanently extends the exclusion from gross income for student loans discharged due to death or total and permanent disability. It expands the definition of covered loans to include private education loans under the Consumer Credit Protection Act. A valid Social Security number is required for the taxpayer to claim this exclusion. These amendments apply to discharges after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70120**
This section permanently extends the limitation on the deduction for state and local taxes (SALT) but significantly increases the cap to $40,000 for taxable years beginning in 2025. The cap is indexed for inflation at 101 percent annually until 2030, after which it reverts to $10,000. The deduction phases out for taxpayers with modified adjusted gross income exceeding $500,000 ($250,000 for separate filers) at a rate of 30 percent. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70201**
This section creates a new deduction for "qualified tips" received by individuals in occupations that customarily receive tips, with a maximum deduction of $25,000. The deduction phases out for taxpayers with modified adjusted gross income exceeding $150,000 ($300,000 for joint returns) at a rate of $100 for every $1,000 of excess income. It also expands the tip credit for employers to include beauty service businesses like barbers and nail technicians. These amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70202**
This section creates a new deduction for "qualified overtime compensation" paid to employees, with a maximum deduction of $12,500 ($25,000 for joint returns). The deduction phases out for taxpayers with modified adjusted gross income exceeding $150,000 ($300,000 for joint returns) at a rate of $100 for every $1,000 of excess income. It requires employers to report qualified overtime compensation separately on Form W-2. These amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70203**
This section creates a temporary exception to the personal interest disallowance rule, allowing a deduction for interest on loans used to purchase qualified passenger vehicles. The deduction is limited to $10,000 of interest and phases out for taxpayers with modified adjusted gross income exceeding $100,000 ($200,000 for joint returns). The vehicle must be manufactured primarily for use on public streets and have a gross vehicle weight rating of less than 14,000 pounds. These changes apply to indebtedness incurred after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70204**
This section establishes "Trump Accounts," a new type of individual retirement account for individuals under age 18, with a contribution limit of $5,000 per year. It allows for a pilot program where the Secretary of the Treasury may contribute $1,000 to the Trump account of an eligible child born between 2025 and 2028. Employers may also contribute up to $2,500 per employee or dependent to these accounts. These provisions apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70301**
This section makes 100 percent bonus depreciation permanent for qualified business property, allowing immediate expensing of the full cost of assets. It extends the 100 percent expensing to certain plants with longer production periods and self-constructed property. A transitional election allows taxpayers to elect a reduced expensing percentage of 40 percent or 60 percent for property placed in service in the first taxable year ending after January 19, 2025. These changes apply to property acquired after January 19, 2025.

**Sec. 70302**
This section allows for the immediate deduction of domestic research and experimental expenditures, repealing the requirement to amortize them over five or fifteen years. It creates a new section 174A to specifically address domestic research, while foreign research expenses continue to be amortized over 15 years. Small businesses may elect to apply this change retroactively to expenditures paid or incurred after December 31, 2021. These amendments apply to amounts paid or incurred in taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70303**
This section permanently extends the floor plan financing interest exception for certain trailers and campers designed for recreational use. It removes the expiration date of December 31, 2021, for the business interest limitation exception regarding floor plan financing. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70304**
This section permanently extends and enhances the paid family and medical leave credit, allowing employers to claim a credit based on wages paid or insurance premiums incurred. It expands the definition of qualifying employees to include those customarily employed for at least 20 hours per week and allows for a 6-month election period. The credit calculation now disregards whether leave was actually taken if an insurance policy is in place. These amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70305**
This section creates exceptions to the 50 percent limitation on business meal deductions for meals provided on fishing vessels or at fish processing facilities located north of 50 degrees latitude. It also allows for the full deduction of meals provided in connection with certain fishing activities. These changes apply to amounts paid or incurred after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70306**
This section permanently increases the dollar limitations for Section 179 expensing of depreciable business assets to $2,500,000, with a phase-out threshold of $4,000,000. It adjusts the inflation indexing base year for these amounts to 2024. These changes apply to property placed in service in taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70307**
This section creates a new 100 percent special depreciation allowance for qualified production property, defined as nonresidential real property used in manufacturing or refining tangible personal property. The property must be placed in service in the United States between January 19, 2025, and January 1, 2031. This allowance applies to the construction of new facilities or the acquisition of used property that was not previously used in qualified production activities. These changes apply to property placed in service after the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70308**
This section permanently increases the advanced manufacturing investment credit from 25 percent to 35 percent for qualified property placed in service. This enhancement applies to property placed in service after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70309**
This section amends the exempt facility bond rules to treat spaceports similarly to airports, allowing them to issue tax-exempt bonds. It defines a spaceport as a facility used for manufacturing, assembling, or repairing spacecraft, or for launch and reentry services. It also clarifies that spaceport property leased from the United States by a governmental unit is treated as owned by that governmental unit. These changes apply to obligations issued after the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70311**
This section modifies the foreign tax credit limitation rules by allocating specific deductions, such as the Section 250 deduction, to foreign source net CFC tested income. It prohibits the allocation of interest expense and research expenditures to this specific category of foreign income. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70312**
This section increases the deemed paid foreign tax credit percentage from 80 percent to 90 percent for taxes attributable to tested income. It also disallows the foreign tax credit for 10 percent of foreign taxes paid on distributions of previously taxed net CFC tested income. These amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70313**
This section modifies sourcing rules for income from the sale of inventory produced in the United States but sold through foreign branches. It treats up to 50 percent of such income as foreign source if the inventory is produced in the U.S. and sold outside the U.S. through a foreign office. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70321**
This section permanently reduces the deduction for foreign-derived deduction eligible income from 37.5 percent to 33.34 percent and the deduction for net CFC tested income from 50 percent to 40 percent. It also repeals the provision allowing for a deduction for global intangible low-taxed income. These amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70322**
This section modifies the determination of deduction eligible income by including income from the sale of intangible property and other depreciable assets in the calculation. It limits the apportionment of expenses to those properly allocable to the gross income, excluding interest and research expenditures. These changes apply to sales occurring after June 16, 2025.

**Sec. 70323**
This section permanently replaces the term "global intangible low-taxed income" with "net CFC tested income" throughout the Internal Revenue Code. It repeals the tax-free deemed return on foreign investments and simplifies the calculation of the deduction for foreign-derived deduction eligible income. These amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70331**
This section permanently extends the Base Erosion Minimum Tax (BEAT) and increases the minimum tax rate from 10 percent to 10.5 percent. It also adjusts the threshold for large taxpayers and modifies the definition of a registered securities dealer. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70341**
This section clarifies the coordination between the business interest limitation and interest capitalization provisions, ensuring the limitation applies regardless of whether interest is deducted or capitalized. It mandates that the allowed amount of business interest is applied first to capitalized interest before being applied to deductible interest. Capitalized interest is no longer treated as business interest for the purpose of the limitation. These amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70342**
This section expands the definition of Adjusted Taxable Income (ATI) for the business interest limitation to include amounts from foreign income inclusions under Sections 951, 951A, and 78. This change aims to prevent the erosion of the ATI base through foreign income inclusions. These amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70351**
This section permanently extends the look-thru rule for related controlled foreign corporations, allowing payments between related CFCs to be treated as effectively connected income. It removes the expiration date of December 31, 2025, for this rule. These changes apply to taxable years of foreign corporations beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70352**
This section repeals the election for a 1-month deferral in determining the taxable year of specified foreign corporations. It requires these corporations to align their taxable year with the required year ending after November 30, 2025. A transition rule allows for the allocation of foreign taxes paid in the transition year. These changes apply to taxable years of specified foreign corporations beginning after November 30, 2025.

**Sec. 70353**
This section restores the limitation on downward attribution of stock ownership, preventing a U.S. person from being treated as owning stock owned by a non-U.S. person. It creates a new category of "foreign controlled United States shareholder" and "foreign controlled foreign corporation" for tax purposes. These provisions apply to taxable years of foreign corporations beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70354**
This section modifies the pro rata share rules for Subpart F income, requiring U.S. shareholders to include their share of income based on ownership on any day during the CFC year. It also allows the Secretary to prescribe regulations for closing the taxable year of a CFC upon a disposition of stock. These changes apply to taxable years of foreign corporations beginning after December 31, 2025. [end of text]


